[2] Pakistan (KPTD) update - EpiCore Surveillance Project
Date: Wed 8 May 2019
Source: EpiCore Global Surveillance Project [edited]

[re: ProMED-mail Poliomyelitis update (33): Pakistan (KPTD, SD) follow-up on prev. conf case, RFI 20190508.6460248]
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
In response to a request for information sent to the EpiCore Surveillance Project members, we received the following information on this new case:

The patient is a 36-month-old child from Miran Ali in North Waziristan, who was diagnosed as having Guillan Barré Syndrome (GBS). The child did not have a history of any routine immunizations and it was questionable if the child had received OPV doses during the polio vaccination campaigns.

--
Communicated by:
EpiCore Global Surveillance Project
<promed@promedmail.org>

[We are very grateful to EpiCore Surveillance Project members for the rapid and very helpful reply to the request for information sent yesterday [8 May 2019].

GBS is a neurologic disorder resulting from the body having an immune response to its peripheral nervous system resulting in an ascending paralysis (starting in the feet and progressing upwards) accompanied by a loss of sensation. While its etiology is not fully understood, it is typically observed to occur several weeks following an upper respiratory or gastrointestinal infection. Paralysis resolves in the majority of cases.

A map showing the districts and provinces of Pakistan can be found at https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/pak215_pakistan_districts_v5_a0_20181203.pdf. Miran Ali is located in North Waziristan.

The HealthMap/ProMED map of Pakistan can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6462140,1184. - Mod.MPP]

